{"title_page": "Maru-a-Pula School", "text_new": "{{short description|Independent school in Gaborone, Botswana}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=August 2018}}\n{{advert|date=August 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=August 2018}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=August 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name = Maru-a-Pula School (MaP)\n|established = 1972\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]]\n|location = [[Gaborone]], [[Botswana]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|-24.6472|25.9329|type:edu_region:BW|display=inline,title}}\n|enrollment = over 750\n|faculty = about 70\n|staff = Principal: Andrew Taylor\n}}\n\n'''Maru-a-Pula School''' is a [[co-educational]], [[independent school|independent]] day and boarding [[secondary school]] in [[Gaborone]], [[Botswana]]. It was founded in 1972.   \n\nThe school prepares students for the [[Cambridge International General Certificate of Education]] (IGCSE), Advanced Subsidiary (AS) and Advanced (A) Level examinations.  \n\n2018 enrollment is a record 780 students :\n\n* Approximately two-thirds are Batswana (citizens of Botswana) \n* 270 are expatriates from 35 different nationalities including United States, [[India]], [[England]], [[South Africa]], [[China]], [[Zimbabwe]], and Egypt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maruapula.org/mission/|title=Maru-a-Pula School|date=8 August 2018|website=Maru-a-Pula School}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\n[[File:Netball at MaP.jpg|thumb|400x400px|MaP's successful U19 Netball Team (2018 ISSSA Champions)]]\nThe school has an afternoon programme known as 'SPE': S for service, P for physical and E for enrichment activities. \n\nService engages students in over 20 community projects. It is mandatory to participate in at least one service as part of your SPEs.<ref>{{cite web |first1= |title=SPE Report |url=http://www.maruapula.org/2018-spe-report |website=www.maruapula.org}}</ref>\n\nThe physical programme includes athletics, basketball, cricket, football, netball, rugby, softball, swimming, tennis and volleyball as well as non-competitive activities such as aerobics, yoga, squash, golf and dance. Forms of dance include Hip Hop, Korean Pop, ballroom and Bollywood (Indian).\n\nEnrichment activities include a marimba band, an a cappella singing group, Setswana choir and a range of clubs. These include clubs for wildlife, debating, chess, poetry, investment, bridge, clay, film, decoupage, sewing, cookery, conversational Chinese and card games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maruapula.org/spe/|title=Maru-a-Pula School SPE|website=Maru-a-Pula School}}</ref> Students can receive individual tuition in various musical instruments.\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{official website|http://www.maruapula.org/}}\n* [http://www.afmap.org/ American Friends of Maru-a-Pula]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Gaborone]]\n[[Category:International schools in Gaborone]]\n[[Category:Schools in Botswana]]\n{{portal|Schools}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maru-a-Pula School}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Independent school in Gaborone, Botswana}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=August 2018}}\n{{advert|date=August 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=August 2018}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=August 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name = Maru-a-Pula School (MaP)\n|established = 1972\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]]\n|location = [[Gaborone]], [[Botswana]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|-24.6472|25.9329|type:edu_region:BW|display=inline,title}}\n|enrollment = over 750\n|faculty = about 70\n|staff = Principal: Andrew Taylor\n}}\n\n'''Maru-a-Pula School''' is a [[co-educational]], [[independent school|independent]] day and boarding [[secondary school]] in [[Gaborone]], [[Botswana]]. It was founded in 1972.   \n\nThe school prepares students for the [[Cambridge International General Certificate of Education]] (IGCSE), Advanced Subsidiary (AS) and Advanced (A) Level examinations.  \n\n2018 enrollment is a record 780 students :\n\n* Approximately two-thirds are Batswana (citizens of Botswana) \n* 270 are expatriates from 35 different nationalities including United States, [[India]], [[England]], [[South Africa]], [[China]], [[Zimbabwe]], and Egypt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maruapula.org/mission/|title=Maru-a-Pula School|date=8 August 2018|website=Maru-a-Pula School}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\n[[File:Netball at MaP.jpg|thumb|400x400px|MaP's successful U19 Netball Team (2018 ISSSA Champions)]]\nThe school has an afternoon programme known as 'SPE': S for service, P for physical and E for enrichment activities. \n\nService engages students in over 20 community projects. It is mandatory to participate in at least one service as part of your SPEs.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Maru-a-Pula |title=SPE Report |url=http://www.maruapula.org/2018-spe-report |website=www.maruapula.org}}</ref>\n\nThe physical programme includes athletics, basketball, cricket, football, netball, rugby, softball, swimming, tennis and volleyball as well as non-competitive activities such as aerobics, yoga, squash, golf and dance. Forms of dance include Hip Hop, Korean Pop, ballroom and Bollywood (Indian).\n\nEnrichment activities include a marimba band, an a cappella singing group, Setswana choir and a range of clubs. These include clubs for wildlife, debating, chess, poetry, investment, bridge, clay, film, decoupage, sewing, cookery, conversational Chinese and card games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maruapula.org/spe/|title=Maru-a-Pula School SPE|website=Maru-a-Pula School}}</ref> Students can receive individual tuition in various musical instruments.\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{official website|http://www.maruapula.org/}}\n* [http://www.afmap.org/ American Friends of Maru-a-Pula]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Gaborone]]\n[[Category:International schools in Gaborone]]\n[[Category:Schools in Botswana]]\n{{portal|Schools}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maru-a-Pula School}}\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActivities:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maru-a-Pula_School"}
{"title_page": "Framestore", "text_new": "{{for|the computer graphics concept|framebuffer}}\n{{advert|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Framestore\n| logo =  File:Framestore office exterior.jpg \n| slogan =\n| predecessor = \n| successor  = \n| foundation = 1986\n| defunct = \n| location =  United Kingdom, United States, Canada\n| industry = [[Motion picture]] [[visual effects|special visual effects]]\n| key_people =  \n| products = Visual effects\n| num_employees = <!--peak number of employees-->\n| parent = <!--None-->Cultural Investment Holdings| subsid = <!--None-->\n}}\n\n'''Framestore''' is a [[Great Britain|British]] [[animation]] and [[visual effects]] company based on [[Chancery Lane]] in [[London]]. Formed in 1986, it acquired (and subsequently merged) the Computer Film Company in 1997. The company works across several different areas of the media: feature films, commercials, music videos, feature animation and digital. Framestore employs about 2,500 staff - 1,000 in London, and 1,500 spread across offices in Chicago, New York, Los Angeles, Montreal, Pune in India and Beijing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Daniel |title=Hollywood's go-to visual effects company |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43211126 |website=BBC News |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Foundation===\nFramestore was founded in 1986 by Sharon Reed, [[William Sargent]], Jonathan Hills, Mike McGee and Alison Turner.<ref>{{cite web |title=CGI (computer-generated imagery) in Movies |url=http://www.hollywoodlexicon.com/cgi.html |website=Hollywood Lexicon |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> [[Tim Webber]] joined Framestore in 1988 and led the company's push into digital film and television, developing Framestore's [[virtual camera]] and motion rig systems. In 1992, Mike Milne started the [[CGI animation|CGI]] department, adding computer-generated animation to the company's range of facilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lifetime Achievement Award |url=https://rts.org.uk/award/rts-craft-and-design-winners-2008 |website=Royal Television Society |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> The company's work covered award-winning images in commercials, music videos, television graphics and television drama. In 1994 its film visual effects division was set up.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n===Merger with CFC===\n[[File:Framestore offices London March 2014.jpg|thumb|Framestore office exterior in London, March 2014, after ''Gravity'' [[BAFTA Award|BAFTA]] wins]]\nIn 1997 Framestore acquired the '''Computer Film Company''' ('''CFC'''), which was one of the UK's first digital film special effects companies, developing technology for digital film scanning, [[compositing]], and output. CFC was founded in London in 1984 by Mike Boudry, Wolfgang Lempp (now CTO at [[Filmlight]]) and Neil Harris ([[Lightworks]]). CFC's first film was ''[[The Fruit Machine (1988 film)|The Fruit Machine]]'', in 1988, which utilised early morphing techniques.<ref name=FRUIT>Rickitt, Richard (2000). ''Special Effects: The History and Technique''. London: Virgin Publishing. {{ISBN|0-8230-7733-0}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Framestore opened their first satellite office in [[New York City]], to focus on [[advertising]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Filer |first1=Joey |title=Interview with Framestore President James Razzall |url=https://reelchicago.com/article/james-razzall/ |website=Reel Chicago |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> This was followed by another office in [[Iceland]] in 2008, which has since been closed and has reopened as a local VFX company, RVX.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biography of Dadi Einarsson |url=http://barsvfx.com/rvx-dadi-einarsson/ |website=Barcelona International Arts & VFX Fair 2019 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> In 2013 Framestore opened an office in [[Montreal]], followed by another in [[Los Angeles]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Brendan |title=Framestore's visual effects won an Oscar, built a Montreal home base |url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/framestores-visual-effects-won-an-oscar-built-a-montreal-home-base |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Canadienne |first1=Presse |title=Visual-effects studio Framestore to add 150 jobs in Montreal |url=https://montrealgazette.com/business/local-business/visual-effects-studio-framestore-to-add-150-jobs-in-montreal |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Christiansen |first1=Mark |title=Framestore Los Angeles |url=https://blog.frame.io/2016/08/30/crib-framestore-los-angeles/ |website=Frame.io Insider |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> In 2014, it launched a production arm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/news/framestore-launches-prod-n-arm-1117939631/|title=Framestore launches prod\u2019n arm|last=Dawtrey|first=Adam|last2=Dawtrey|first2=Adam|date=2006-03-13|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n\nEarly projects for the company include the delivery of its first feature animation project ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' with Universal;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Desowitz |first1=Bill |title=Building a Better Mousetrap for 'Despereaux' |url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/building-better-mousetrap-despereaux |website=Animation World Network |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> the completion of Europe's first [[digital intermediate]] for the film ''[[Chicken Run]]'' in 2000;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bosley |first1=Rachael K. |title=A Model Thriller |url=https://theasc.com/magazine/oct05/curse/page1.html |website=American Cinematographer |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> contribution of scenes for the 2009 film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frei |first1=Vincent |title=AVATAR: Jonathan Fawkner,VFX Supervisor, Framestore |url=https://www.artofvfx.com/avatar-jonathan-fawkner-vfx-supervisor-framestore/ |website=Art of VFX |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> and the completion as a production project of four British feature films which opened in theatres between during 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Todd |title=Me and Orson Welles |url=https://variety.com/2008/film/markets-festivals/me-and-orson-welles-1200470866/ |website=Variety Magazine |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisition by CIH ===\nIn November 2016, Framestore agreed to let the [[Shanghai]]-based Cultural Investment Holdings Co acquire 75% of it for \u00a3112.50 million.<ref name=GUARD>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/03/framestore-sale-china-group-harry-potter-paddington-doctor-strange|title=Harry Potter special effects firm looks east with sale to China group|last=Kollewe|first=Julia|date=3 November 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=4 November 2016}}</ref> At the time, Framestore had its main base in London Soho, and additional offices in New York, Montreal, and Los Angeles, employing around 1,400 staff. It was also working on projects such as ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and ''[[Paddington 2]].''<ref name=CHINESE>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.cartoonbrew.com/vfx/gravity-dr-strange-vfx-studio-framestore-bought-chinese-firm-144472.html\n | title =\t\u2018Gravity,\u2019 \u2018Dr. Strange\u2019 VFX Studio Framestore Bought by Chinese Firm\n | last =Failes\n | first =Ian\n | date =3 November 2016\n | publisher =CartoonBrew\n | access-date =3 November 2016\n | quote = }}</ref> In April 2017, Framestore opened a third US location, in [[Chicago, Illinois]].<ref name=CHICAGO>{{cite web\n | url =http://www.thedrum.com/news/2017/04/27/framestore-opening-third-us-location-chicago\n | title =\tFramestore opening third US location in Chicago\n | last =O'Brien\n | first =Kyle\n | date =27 April 2017\n | publisher =TheDrum\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nThe company also worked on the 2017 film ''[[Darkest Hour (film)|Darkest Hour]]'' directed by [[Joe Wright]], working out of the Montreal facility of Framestore to create historically accurate backdrops for 85 shots in the film, including battle scenes.<ref name=DARKEST>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.creativereview.co.uk/how-framestore-recreated-history-in-darkest-hour/\n | title = Film Week: How Framestore Recreated History in Darkest Hour\n | last =Williams\n | first =Eliza\n | date =2 February 2018\n | publisher =Creative Review\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nThe team created around 300 shots for the 2017 film ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'', with Framestore winning a special visual effects award at the 2018 [[British Academy Film Awards]].<ref name=AWARDS>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.awn.com/news/framestore-celebrates-bafta-vfx-win-blade-runner-2049\n | title =\tFramestore Celebrates BAFTA VFX win for 'Blade Runner 2049'\n | last =McLean\n | first =Tom\n | date =20 February 2018\n | publisher =AWN\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref> They have also worked on ''[[Black Mirror]]'', creating props such as the 60s-style spaceship in the premiere of the fourth season.<ref name=BM>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/how-framestore-created-60s-style-spaceship-in-black-mirror-season-4-episode-1/\n | title =How Framestore created the 60s-style spaceship in Black Mirror Season 4, Episode 1\n | last =Harris\n | first =Miriam\n | date =4 January 2018\n | publisher =Digital Arts Online\n | access-date =3 November 2016\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nIn its current incarnation, Framestore delivers images for feature films, television drama, advertising, console and online games, internet and mobile phone applications, and at one point has been Europe's largest post-production house.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Accolades==\nCFC has been awarded two [[Academy Award, Scientific or Technical|Scientific and Technical Academy Awards]], and 14 Primetime Emmys. In 2008, Framestore won their first Oscar for [[Academy Award for Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] for the film ''[[The Golden Compass (film)|The Golden Compass]]''; they also won the [[BAFTA]] Award for that film the same year. Framestore was also nominated for Oscars in 2007 (''[[Superman Returns]]''), in 2009 (''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'') and again in 2010 (''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n[[Tim Webber]] was the VFX supervisor on ''[[Gravity (2013 film)|Gravity]]'' (2013), and the techniques involved in the film realised by Webber and the Framestore team took three years to complete.<ref name=STAND>[https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/tim-webber-the-man-who-put-sandra-bullock-in-space-8804917.html \"Tim Webber: the man who put Sandra Bullock in space\"]. Evening Standard. Retrieved 17 January 2014</ref> The team won the best visual effects awards [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects]] at the [[67th British Academy Film Awards]], and the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]] award at the [[86th Academy Awards]].<ref name=SAM>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Alex|title=Gravity's Oscar-Winning Visual Effects Mastermind Talks about Computer Graphics and \"Weightlessness\"|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/gravitys-oscar-winning-visual-effects-mastermind-talks-about-computer-graphics-and-weightlessness/|publisher=Nature SoapBox Science|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref> \n \nIn advertising the team has also won major awards including [[Cannes Lions]], [[British Television Advertising Awards]], [[Clios]], [[D&AD]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Milligan |first1=Mercedes |title=Framestore Opens 3rd US Shop in Chicago |url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/vfx/framestore-opens-3rd-us-shop-in-chicago/ |website=Animation Magazine |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's R&D team spun off to create the technology company Filmlight, which in 2010 received four Scientific Academy Awards.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Advertising and trade characters==\nFramestore has collaborated with companies and advertising agencies to create trade characters, and also created an attempted [[Photorealism|photorealistic]] computer-generated [[Audrey Hepburn]] for a [[Galaxy (chocolate)|Galaxy]] advert. A combination of elements including [[body double]]s, [[motion capture]], [[Facial Action Coding System|FACS]] and a lighting program called Arnold were used to mimic the appearance of the actress 20 years after her death. The advert drew press attention both for the cutting edge technology utilized and the ethical implications of using a person's likeness posthumously for commercial purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/features/2016/04/how-london-became-the-home-of-hollywood-vfx/|title=From Paintbox to PC: How London became the home of Hollywood VFX|last=Walton|first=Mark|date=2016-04-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-world-if/2018/07/05/performance-anxiety|title=Performance anxiety|date=2018-07-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-03-18|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/apr/10/bruce-lee-audrey-hepburn-ethics-digital-necromancy|title=Bruce Lee, Audrey Hepburn and the ethics of digital necromancy|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2015-04-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Film projects==\n===Recent===\n* ''[[The Suicide Squad (film)|The Suicide Squad]]'' (2021)\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry (2020 film)|Tom and Jerry]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Army of the Dead (upcoming film)|Army of the Dead]]''\n* ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]] (2020)\n* ''[[Untitled Schulman/Joost project]]''\n* ''[[Wonder Woman 1984]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[No Time to Die (2020 film)|No Time to Die]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[The King's Man]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Lady and the Tramp (2019 film)|Lady and the Tramp]]'' (2019)''\n* ''[[Fast & Furious Presents: Hobbs & Shaw]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Detective Pikachu]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Dumbo (2019 film)|Dumbo]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Alita: Battle Angel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Mary Poppins Returns]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Christopher Robin (film)|Christopher Robin]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Paddington 2]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Geostorm]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Kingsman: The Golden Circle]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Alien: Covenant]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Doctor Strange (2016 film)|Doctor Strange]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Pan (2015 film)|Pan]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Martian (film)|The Martian]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Everest (2015 film)|Everest]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron|Avengers: Age Of Ultron]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Paddington (film)|Paddington]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Dracula Untold]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Edge of Tomorrow (film)|Edge of Tomorrow]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Gravity (2013 film)|Gravity]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Wrath of the Titans]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Clash of the Titans (2010 film)|Clash of the Titans]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Harry Brown (film)|Harry Brown]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' (2010) and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2|Part 2]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Nanny McPhee and the Big Bang]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time (film)|Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Salt (2010 film)|Salt]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes (2009 film)|Sherlock Holmes]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Your Highness]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' (2010)\n* [[Coca-Cola]] ''Siege'' advertisement ([[Super Bowl XLV]])<ref name=COLA>{{cite web|url=http://www.coca-colacompany.com/press-center/press-releases/#TCCC |title=Coca-Cola - Press Center - Press Kits - \"Coke Cheers\" And Boys & Girls Clubs Of America |publisher=coca-colacompany.com |date= |accessdate=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[We Steal Secrets: The Story of WikiLeaks]]'' (2013)\n\n===Past===\n<!--If you've come to add one, make sure to keep this in alphabetical order.-->\n* ''[[The Affair of the Necklace]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[The Ballad of Big Al]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Beach (film)|The Beach]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Blade II]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[The Bone Collector]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Bright Young Things (film)|Bright Young Things]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Cast Away]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Chased by Dinosaurs]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Ch\u00e9ri (film)|Cheri]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Chicken Run]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Children of Men]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[A Close Shave]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Cold Lazarus]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Cold Mountain (film)|Cold Mountain]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Constant Gardener (film)|The Constant Gardener]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Die Another Day]]'' (2002) - title sequence only\n* ''[[Dinotopia (miniseries)|Dinotopia]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Doctor Who]]'' - title sequence only\n* ''[[Doom (film)|Doom]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The End of the Affair (1999 film)|The End of the Affair]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Enduring Love (film)|Enduring Love]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Enemy at the Gates]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Eyes Wide Shut]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The 51st State]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Goal! (film)|Goal]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Golden Compass (film)|The Golden Compass]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Good Thief (film)|The Good Thief]]'' (2002) & ''[[Dirty Pretty Things (film)|Dirty Pretty Things]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Jacket]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Last Dragon (2004 film)|The Last Dragon]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Layer Cake (film)|Layer Cake]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Lost World (2001 film)|The Lost World]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Love Actually]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Mamma Mia! (film)|Mamma Mia]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Mission: Impossible 2]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Mummy Returns]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Nanny McPhee]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[noitulovE]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Notting Hill (film)|Notting Hill]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Primeval (TV series)|Primeval]]'' (2007\u201311)\n* ''[[Prehistoric Park]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Proposition (2005 film)|The Proposition]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Resident Evil (1996 video game)|Resident Evil]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Sahara (2005 film)|Sahara]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sea (Smirnoff)|Sea]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Sea Monsters (TV series)|Sea Monsters]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Sexy Beast]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Skyfall]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Sleepy Hollow (film)|Sleepy Hollow]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Superman Returns]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' (2008) - under Framestore Feature Animation\n* ''[[Thunderbirds (2004 film)|Thunderbirds]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Underdog (2007 film)|Underdog]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Underworld (2003 film)|Underworld]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[V for Vendetta (film)|V for Vendetta]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Walking with Beasts]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Walking with Cavemen]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Walking with Monsters]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Wanted (2008 film)|Wanted]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[What Lies Beneath]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Where the Wild Things Are (film)|Where the Wild Things Are]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'' (2006)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Weta Digital]]\n* [[Industrial Light & Magic]]\n*[[Moving Picture Company|Moving Picture Company (MPC)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.framestore.com}}\n* {{imdb company|0105094|The Computer Film Company}}\n*[https://www.wired.co.uk/article/the-image-engineers Wired article on the company]\n\n{{coord |51|30|54.2|N|0|8|11.7|W|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM|display=title}}\n\n{{Animation industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Visual effects companies]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Best Visual Effects Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Computer animation]]\n[[Category:British animation studios]]\n[[Category:Special effects companies]]\n[[Category:Television and film post-production companies]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{ad|date=November 2019}}\n{{for|the computer graphics concept|framebuffer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Framestore\n| logo =  File:Framestore office exterior.jpg \n| slogan =\n| predecessor = \n| successor  = \n| foundation = 1986\n| defunct = \n| location =  United Kingdom, United States, Canada\n| industry = [[Motion picture]] [[visual effects|special visual effects]]\n| key_people =  \n| products = Visual effects\n| num_employees = <!--peak number of employees-->\n| parent = <!--None-->Cultural Investment Holdings| subsid = <!--None-->\n}}\n\n'''Framestore''' is a [[Great Britain|British]] [[animation]] and [[visual effects]] company based on [[Chancery Lane]] in [[London]]. Formed in 1986, it acquired (and subsequently merged) the Computer Film Company in 1997. The company works across several different areas of the media: feature films, commercials, music videos, feature animation and digital. Framestore employs about 2,500 staff - 1,000 in London, and 1,500 spread across offices in Chicago, New York, Los Angeles, Montreal, Pune in India and Beijing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Daniel |title=Hollywood's go-to visual effects company |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43211126 |website=BBC News |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Foundation===\nFramestore was founded in 1986 by Sharon Reed, [[William Sargent]], Jonathan Hills, Mike McGee and Alison Turner.<ref>{{cite web |title=CGI (computer-generated imagery) in Movies |url=http://www.hollywoodlexicon.com/cgi.html |website=Hollywood Lexicon |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> [[Tim Webber]] joined Framestore in 1988 and led the company's push into digital film and television, developing Framestore\u2019s [[virtual camera]] and motion rig systems. In 1992, Mike Milne started the [[CGI animation|CGI]] department, adding computer-generated animation to the company\u2019s range of facilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lifetime Achievement Award |url=https://rts.org.uk/award/rts-craft-and-design-winners-2008 |website=Royal Television Society |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> The company's work covered award-winning images in commercials, music videos, television graphics and television drama. In 1994 its film visual effects division was set up.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n===Merger with CFC===\n[[File:Framestore offices London March 2014.jpg|thumb|Framestore office exterior in London, March 2014, after ''Gravity'' [[BAFTA Award|BAFTA]] wins]]\nIn 1997 Framestore acquired the '''Computer Film Company''' ('''CFC'''), which was one of the UK's first digital film special effects companies, developing technology for digital film scanning, [[compositing]], and output. CFC was founded in London in 1984 by Mike Boudry, Wolfgang Lempp (now CTO at [[Filmlight]]) and Neil Harris ([[Lightworks]]). CFC's first film was ''[[The Fruit Machine (1988 film)|The Fruit Machine]]'', in 1988, which utilised early morphing techniques.<ref name=FRUIT>Rickitt, Richard (2000). ''Special Effects: The History and Technique''. London: Virgin Publishing. {{ISBN|0-8230-7733-0}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Framestore opened their first satellite office in [[New York City]], to focus on [[advertising]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Filer |first1=Joey |title=Interview with Framestore President James Razzall |url=https://reelchicago.com/article/james-razzall/ |website=Reel Chicago |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> This was followed by another office in [[Iceland]] in 2008, which has since been closed and has reopened as a local VFX company, RVX.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biography of Dadi Einarsson |url=http://barsvfx.com/rvx-dadi-einarsson/ |website=Barcelona International Arts & VFX Fair 2019 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> In 2013 Framestore opened an office in [[Montreal]], followed by another in [[Los Angeles]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Brendan |title=Framestore's visual effects won an Oscar, built a Montreal home base |url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/framestores-visual-effects-won-an-oscar-built-a-montreal-home-base |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Canadienne |first1=Presse |title=Visual-effects studio Framestore to add 150 jobs in Montreal |url=https://montrealgazette.com/business/local-business/visual-effects-studio-framestore-to-add-150-jobs-in-montreal |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Christiansen |first1=Mark |title=Framestore Los Angeles |url=https://blog.frame.io/2016/08/30/crib-framestore-los-angeles/ |website=Frame.io Insider |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> In 2014, it launched a production arm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/news/framestore-launches-prod-n-arm-1117939631/|title=Framestore launches prod\u2019n arm|last=Dawtrey|first=Adam|last2=Dawtrey|first2=Adam|date=2006-03-13|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n\nEarly projects for the company include the delivery of its first feature animation project ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' with Universal;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Desowitz |first1=Bill |title=Building a Better Mousetrap for 'Despereaux' |url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/building-better-mousetrap-despereaux |website=Animation World Network |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> the completion of Europe's first [[digital intermediate]] for the film ''[[Chicken Run]]'' in 2000;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bosley |first1=Rachael K. |title=A Model Thriller |url=https://theasc.com/magazine/oct05/curse/page1.html |website=American Cinematographer |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> contribution of scenes for the 2009 film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frei |first1=Vincent |title=AVATAR: Jonathan Fawkner,VFX Supervisor, Framestore |url=https://www.artofvfx.com/avatar-jonathan-fawkner-vfx-supervisor-framestore/ |website=Art of VFX |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> and the completion as a production project of four British feature films which opened in theatres between during 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Todd |title=Me and Orson Welles |url=https://variety.com/2008/film/markets-festivals/me-and-orson-welles-1200470866/ |website=Variety Magazine |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisition by CIH ===\nIn November 2016, Framestore agreed to let the [[Shanghai]]-based Cultural Investment Holdings Co acquire 75% of it for \u00a3112.50 million.<ref name=GUARD>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/03/framestore-sale-china-group-harry-potter-paddington-doctor-strange|title=Harry Potter special effects firm looks east with sale to China group|last=Kollewe|first=Julia|date=3 November 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=4 November 2016}}</ref> At the time, Framestore had its main base in London Soho, and additional offices in New York, Montreal, and Los Angeles, employing around 1,400 staff. It was also working on projects such as ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and ''[[Paddington 2]].''<ref name=CHINESE>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.cartoonbrew.com/vfx/gravity-dr-strange-vfx-studio-framestore-bought-chinese-firm-144472.html\n | title =\t\u2018Gravity,\u2019 \u2018Dr. Strange\u2019 VFX Studio Framestore Bought by Chinese Firm\n | last =Failes\n | first =Ian\n | date =3 November 2016\n | publisher =CartoonBrew\n | access-date =3 November 2016\n | quote = }}</ref> In April 2017, Framestore opened a third US location, in [[Chicago, Illinois]].<ref name=CHICAGO>{{cite web\n | url =http://www.thedrum.com/news/2017/04/27/framestore-opening-third-us-location-chicago\n | title =\tFramestore opening third US location in Chicago\n | last =O'Brien\n | first =Kyle\n | date =27 April 2017\n | publisher =TheDrum\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nThe company also worked on the 2017 film ''[[Darkest Hour (film)|Darkest Hour]]'' directed by [[Joe Wright]], working out of the Montreal facility of Framestore to create historically accurate backdrops for 85 shots in the film, including battle scenes.<ref name=DARKEST>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.creativereview.co.uk/how-framestore-recreated-history-in-darkest-hour/\n | title = Film Week: How Framestore Recreated History in Darkest Hour\n | last =Williams\n | first =Eliza\n | date =2 February 2018\n | publisher =Creative Review\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nThe team created around 300 shots for the 2017 film ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'', with Framestore winning a special visual effects award at the 2018 [[British Academy Film Awards]].<ref name=AWARDS>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.awn.com/news/framestore-celebrates-bafta-vfx-win-blade-runner-2049\n | title =\tFramestore Celebrates BAFTA VFX win for 'Blade Runner 2049'\n | last =McLean\n | first =Tom\n | date =20 February 2018\n | publisher =AWN\n | access-date =28 February 2018\n | quote = }}</ref> They have also worked on ''[[Black Mirror]]'', creating props such as the 60s-style spaceship in the premiere of the fourth season.<ref name=BM>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/how-framestore-created-60s-style-spaceship-in-black-mirror-season-4-episode-1/\n | title =How Framestore created the 60s-style spaceship in Black Mirror Season 4, Episode 1\n | last =Harris\n | first =Miriam\n | date =4 January 2018\n | publisher =Digital Arts Online\n | access-date =3 November 2016\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\nIn its current incarnation, Framestore delivers images for feature films, television drama, advertising, console and online games, internet and mobile phone applications, and at one point has been Europe's largest post-production house.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Accolades==\nCFC has been awarded two [[Academy Award, Scientific or Technical|Scientific and Technical Academy Awards]], and 14 Primetime Emmys. In 2008, Framestore won their first Oscar for [[Academy Award for Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] for the film ''[[The Golden Compass (film)|The Golden Compass]]''; they also won the [[BAFTA]] Award for that film the same year. Framestore was also nominated for Oscars in 2007 (''[[Superman Returns]]''), in 2009 (''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'') and again in 2010 (''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n[[Tim Webber]] was the VFX supervisor on ''[[Gravity (2013 film)|Gravity]]'' (2013), and the techniques involved in the film realised by Webber and the Framestore team took three years to complete.<ref name=STAND>[https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/tim-webber-the-man-who-put-sandra-bullock-in-space-8804917.html \"Tim Webber: the man who put Sandra Bullock in space\"]. Evening Standard. Retrieved 17 January 2014</ref> The team won the best visual effects awards [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects]] at the [[67th British Academy Film Awards]], and the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]] award at the [[86th Academy Awards]].<ref name=SAM>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Alex|title=Gravity's Oscar-Winning Visual Effects Mastermind Talks about Computer Graphics and \"Weightlessness\"|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/gravitys-oscar-winning-visual-effects-mastermind-talks-about-computer-graphics-and-weightlessness/|publisher=Nature SoapBox Science|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref> \n \nIn advertising the team has also won major awards including [[Cannes Lions]], [[British Television Advertising Awards]], [[Clios]], [[D&AD]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Milligan |first1=Mercedes |title=Framestore Opens 3rd US Shop in Chicago |url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/vfx/framestore-opens-3rd-us-shop-in-chicago/ |website=Animation Magazine |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's R&D team spun off to create the technology company Filmlight, which in 2010 received four Scientific Academy Awards.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Advertising and trade characters==\nFramestore has collaborated with companies and advertising agencies to create trade characters, and also created an attempted [[Photorealism|photorealistic]] computer-generated [[Audrey Hepburn]] for a [[Galaxy (chocolate)|Galaxy]] advert. A combination of elements including [[Body double|body doubles]], [[motion capture]], [[Facial Action Coding System|FACS]] and a lighting program called Arnold were used to mimic the appearance of the actress 20 years after her death. The advert drew press attention both for the cutting edge technology utilized and the ethical implications of using a person's likeness posthumously for commercial purposes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/features/2016/04/how-london-became-the-home-of-hollywood-vfx/|title=From Paintbox to PC: How London became the home of Hollywood VFX|last=Walton|first=Mark|date=2016-04-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-world-if/2018/07/05/performance-anxiety|title=Performance anxiety|date=2018-07-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-03-18|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/apr/10/bruce-lee-audrey-hepburn-ethics-digital-necromancy|title=Bruce Lee, Audrey Hepburn and the ethics of digital necromancy|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2015-04-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Film projects==\n===Recent===\n* ''[[The Suicide Squad (film)|The Suicide Squad]]'' (2021)\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry (2020 film)|Tom and Jerry]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Army of the Dead (upcoming film)|Army of the Dead]]''\n* ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]] (2020)\n* ''[[Untitled Schulman/Joost project]]''\n* ''[[Wonder Woman 1984]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[No Time to Die (2020 film)|No Time to Die]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[The Ki